Natural Language Processing

Political Debate Content Analysis Natural Language Processing Project_ Github

I’ve selected the webpage consisting of transcripts of CNN Covers the First Republican Presidential Debate of the 2024 Election, which was aired from 11 p.m. to 12 a.m. ET. The URL for my text is “https://transcripts.cnn.com/show/se/date/2023-08-23/segment/02”. Analyzing a transcript of a significant event, such as the first Republican presidential debate of the 2024 election, provides insights into candidates’ stances, popular topics, public sentiments, and the overall political landscape. This type of analysis is fascinating for various reasons. It helped me understand the political discourse by examining the language used by candidates, moderators, and the audience. I could recognize prevailing political ideologies, rhetorical strategies, and the framing of key issues. Examining how CNN portrays and covers the debate allowed me to shed light on media biases, the framing of issues, and the significance given to different candidates or topics during the event. Analyzing the language used by both moderators and candidates revealed the overall sentiment of the debate, individual sentiments towards specific topics, and the emotional tone conveyed throughout. Dissecting the discussions and debates helped me identify recurring themes such as healthcare, foreign policy, economic plans, and social issues that are critical for voters. Lastly, by analyzing how candidates presented themselves, their debating styles, and how they responded to the questions, I could understand their preparedness and potential appeal to voters.

def normalize(text):
text = tprep.normalize.hyphenated_words(text)
text = tprep.normalize.quotation_marks(text)
text = tprep.normalize.unicode(text)
text = tprep.remove.accents(text)
text = tprep.replace.phone_numbers(text)
text = tprep.replace.urls(text)
text = tprep.replace.emails(text)
text = tprep.replace.user_handles(text)
text = tprep.replace.emojis(text)
return text

re_suspicious = re.compile(r'[&#<>{}\[\]\\]')

def impurity(text, min_len =10):
if text == None or len(text)< min_len:
    return 0
else:
    return len(re_suspicious.findall(text))/len(text)


def clean_up(text, min_len=10):
if pd.notna(text) and len(str(text)) >= min_len:
    # text = html.unescape(str(text))
    text = re.sub(r'<[^<>]*>', ' ', text)
    text = re.sub(r'\[([^\[\]]*)\]\([^\(\)]*\)', r'\1', text)  # [Some text](https://....)
    text = re.sub(r'\[[^\[\]]*\]', ' ', text)  # [0]
    text = re.sub(r'(?:^|\s)[&#<>{}\[\]+|\\:-]{1,}(?:\s|$)', ' ', text)
    text = re.sub(r'(?:^|\s)[\-=\+]{2,}(?:\s|$)', ' ', text)
    text = re.sub(r'\s+', ' ', text)
    text = re.sub(r'\(COMMERCIAL BREAK\)', ' ', text)
    text = re.sub(r'THIS IS A RUSH TRANSCRIPT\. ', ' ', text)
    text = re.sub(r'THIS COPY MAY NOT BE IN ITS FINAL FORM AND MAY BE UPDATED\. ', ' ', text)
    text = re.sub(r'\(APPLAUSE\)', ' ', text)
    text = re.sub(r'\(LAUGHTER\)', ' ', text)
    text = re.sub(r'\(BEGIN VIDEO CLIP\)', ' ', text)
    text = re.sub(r'\(END VIDEO CLIP\)', ' ', text)
    text = re.sub(r'\(BELL RINGING\)', ' ', text)

    return text.strip()
else:
    return ''

def preprocess_text(text):
text = str(text).lower()
text = [str(word) for word in nltk.word_tokenize(str(text)) if word.lower() not in mystopwords and word not in punctuation]
# text = [stemmer.stem(str(word)) for word in text]
text = " ".join(text)
return text

def preprocess(text): 
text = str(text).lower()
return [word for word in nltk.word_tokenize(text) if word.lower() and word.isalpha() and word not in mystopwords and word not in punctuation]

In the processing text section, the problems I encountered were the squared brackets, which indicate the time (e.g., [23:40:00]). This information doesn’t bring any benefit to my analysis, so I used regex to remove all of the unwanted characters and returned the clean text into the new column called ‘clean’. Then I dropped lines containing certain patterns, such as ‘(COMMERCIAL BREAK)’ and other broadcast related tags. That was important to fix because it may affect the result of the calculation of the most common part of POS tagging. I then joined the sentences in the “clean” column, found the specific and universal tag of each word, and put them all in a new DataFrame called DF_tags, making it a better way to implement. I could use techniques such as tokenization to break the text into individual words, stemming to reduce words to their base, or lemmatization to reduce words to their dictionary form as choices to normalize, depending on the goal of my NLP analysis. By examining the most common entities in the text, I could get a general sense of the theme of the text. Verbs signify actions or states of being and could help identify the narrative style of the text. I could note that the text is a “transcript” covering the “CNN Live Event” regarding the “Presidential Debate Election.” I were surprised to note that, upon using spell check and examining the dictionary, it’s not always necessary to replace the words with the corrected ones.

ent_types = ["PERSON", "GPE"]#,"NORP"]
stored_entities = []

def get_entities(x): ## 
  """
  Grabs the names using spacy's entity labeler
  """

processed = nlp(x) 

tokens = [word.text for word in processed]

temp = [(ent.text, ent.label_) for ent in processed.ents if ent.label_ in ent_types]

if len(temp) > 1: 
temp2 = list(combinations(temp, 2))
for (person1, person2) in temp2:
    person1_words = [word.text for word in nlp(person1[0])]
    person1_ids = [i for i, val in enumerate(tokens) if val in person1_words]
    if len(person1_words) > 1:
    person1_ids2 = tuple(idx for idx in person1_ids[0:2])
    else:
    id_1 = [idx for idx in person1_ids]
    person1_ids2 = (id_1[0], id_1[0])
    
    person2_words = [word.text for word in nlp(person2[0])]
    person2_ids = [i for i, val in enumerate(tokens) if val in person2_words[0:2]]
    if len(person2_words) > 1:
    person2_ids2 = tuple(idx for idx in person2_ids)
    else:
    id_2 = [idx for idx in person2_ids]
    person2_ids2 = (id_2[0], id_2[0])  
    
    stored_entities.append(
    [x, # original text
    tokens, # tokens
    person1[0], # person 1 name
    person2[0], # person 2 name
    person1_ids2, # person 1 id token tuple 
    person2_ids2 # person 2 id token tuple
    ])
    
    # Adding custom rule for entity recognition
    for idx, token in enumerate(tokens):
    if token.lower() == "cnn" and idx < len(tokens) - 1 and tokens[idx + 1].lower() in ["host", "commentator"]:
        temp.append(("CNN"))

#words in the middle
@preprocessor()
def get_text_between(cand: DataPoint) -> DataPoint:
    """
    Returns the text between the two person mentions in the sentence
    """
start = cand.person1_word_idx[1] + 1
end = cand.person2_word_idx[0]
cand.between_tokens = " ".join(cand.tokens[start:end])
return cand
In [16]:
# words to the left of each entity
@preprocessor()
def get_left_tokens(cand: DataPoint) -> DataPoint:
    """
    Returns tokens in the length 3 window to the left of the person mentions
    """
# TODO: need to pass window as input params
window = 3

end = cand.person1_word_idx[0]
cand.person1_left_tokens = cand.tokens[0:end][-1 - window : -1]

end = cand.person2_word_idx[0]
cand.person2_left_tokens = cand.tokens[0:end][-1 - window : -1]
return cand

#Get the dataframe into the right format to use these functions

characters = {"senator", "president", "opponent","governor","leader","Republican","American","Commentator", "communists","Party","Congress",}
places = {","}

pos_character = 1
neg_location = -1
no_relation = 0

@labeling_function(resources=dict(characters=characters), pre=[get_text_between])
def between_characters(x, characters):
return pos_character if len(characters.intersection(set(x.between_tokens.lower()))) > 0 else no_relation

@labeling_function(resources=dict(places=places), pre=[get_text_between])
def between_places(x, places):
return neg_location if len(places.intersection(set(x.between_tokens.lower()))) > 0 else no_relation

@labeling_function(resources=dict(characters=characters), pre=[get_left_tokens])
def left_characters(x, characters):
if len(set(characters).intersection(set(x.person1_left_tokens))) > 0:
    return pos_character
elif len(set(characters).intersection(set(x.person2_left_tokens))) > 0:
    return pos_character
else:
    return no_relation

@labeling_function(resources=dict(places=places), pre=[get_left_tokens])
def left_places(x, places):
if len(set(places).intersection(set(x.person1_left_tokens))) > 0:
    return neg_location
elif len(set(places).intersection(set(x.person2_left_tokens))) > 0:
    return neg_location
else:
    return no_relation

### Topic Model

# Create a dictionary representation of the documents.

# first create sentences
sentences = nltk.sent_tokenize(clean_text)

# preprocess those sentences #use gensim
processed_sentences = [preprocess(sent) for sent in sentences]

# create a list of ids to words (0 is cat, 1 is cheese)
dictionary = Dictionary(processed_sentences)

# create the term by document bag of words 
corpus = [dictionary.doc2bow(sent) for sent in processed_sentences]

# Train the topic model
LDAmodel = LdaModel(corpus = corpus,
            id2word = dictionary,
            iterations = 400, 
            num_topics = 10,
            random_state = 5494, 
            update_every = 1,
            chunksize = 100, 
            passes = 10, 
            alpha = 'auto', 
            per_word_topics = True)# 

# get the probability of each sentence's topics                 
probs = [LDAmodel.get_document_topics(sentence) for sentence in corpus]

save_probs = []
i = 0 # this assumes topic 0 is the one you want 
# get only topic zero probabilities for each sentence
for document in probs: 
for (topic, prob) in document: 
if topic == 0:
    save_probs.append((sentences[i], prob)) 
i = i + 1 
    
# put that into a data frame
DF = pd.DataFrame(save_probs, columns = ["sentence", "prob"])

# take the top X probability sentences 
topic_summary = " ".join(DF.sort_values(by = ["prob"], ascending = False)[0:num_summary_sentence].sentence)

topic_summary

It stands out as the best summarization technique. LSA provides a reasonable summary, covering 4 out of the 7 main points, while Topic Model LDA generates less coherent summaries, providing fragmented information without clear coverage of the main ideas. Therefore, TextRank is the most effective summarization technique, followed by LSA, while Topic Model falls short in providing a comprehensive and coherent summary. The results from my topic modeling highlighted three key topics related to the text: political events and diplomacy, base engagement and public communication, and international affairs. Each topic captured specific aspects, such as political events and diplomacy, engaging the political base, and international affairs. Other techniques that might deepen insights would be entity interactions, thematic relationships, and entity co-reference resolution methods that could be employed to reconcile references to the same entity across the text. Integrating these methods enhances overall analysis, particularly in challenging NLP tasks like summarizing political debates.

import numpy as np
def document_vectorizer(corpus, model, num_features):
vocabulary = set(model.wv.index_to_key)
def average_word_vectors(words, model, vocabulary, num_features):
    feature_vector = np.zeros((num_features,), dtype="float64")
    nwords = 0.
    for word in words:
        if word in vocabulary: 
            nwords = nwords + 1.
            feature_vector = np.add(feature_vector, model.wv[word])
    if nwords:
        feature_vector = np.divide(feature_vector, nwords)
    return feature_vector
features = [average_word_vectors(tokenized_sentence, model, vocabulary, num_features)
                for tokenized_sentence in corpus]
return np.array(features)

I decided to preprocess the data in two ways as followed:

  • Preprocess 1: preprocessing text using SpaCy for tokenization and textacy for removing stopwords, punctuations and numbers and then lowering text case by using the for loop to travel through each token.
  • Preprocess 2: insteaad of applying SpaCy, I manually preprocess the text data by first applying word_tokenize of nltk package and use the for loop to go through each token, lowering the case and removing the stopwords and punctuations. Then I also conduct stemming to only extract the stem words.
  • Therefore, for the key terms extraction, I also applied clean_up function and textacy to preprocess the text data. Then, since the second dataset ended up with stem words, we also had to apply stemming for the key terms so that the words are matched with each other and facilitate the labeling process.

#Option Preprocess_1: textacy to preprocess + no stemming

def preprocess_text_1(text):
doc = nlp(text, disable=["tok2vec", "ner", "parser"])
tokens = textacy.extract.words(doc,
        filter_stops = True,           # default True, no stopwords #sometimes stopwords and punctuation kept in information extraction task
        filter_punct = True,           # default True, no punctuation
        filter_nums = True,            # default False, no numbers
        include_pos = None,            # default None = include all
        exclude_pos = None,            # default None = exclude none
        min_freq = 1)                  # minimum frequency of words
text = [str(word).lower() for word in tokens]
text = " ".join(text)
return text


#Option Preprocess_2: manual preprocess + stemming
def preprocess_text_2(text):
text = str(text).lower()
text = [str(word) for word in nltk.word_tokenize(str(text)) if word.lower() not in mystopwords and word not in punctuation]
text = [stemmer.stem(str(word)) for word in text]
text = " ".join(text)
return text

I decided to use TF-IDF and word2vec for feature extractions. The normal trend would be to start with very basic vectorization, like one-hot encoding or bag of words, then implement more complex ones. But I chose to apply TF-IDF here considering one-hot encoding might be more helpful for short texts, and bag of words assumes that all the words are equally important, while TF-IDF applies the normalization procedure that increases the importance of useful words and decreases the importance of overused words. Thus, TF-IDF is represented by weights rather than counts, and ultimately, it'd be more informative. Furthermore, polysemy is one of the big issues in NLP since words can have so many meanings. Understanding the context can help me deal with disambiguity. So the next feature extraction model I selected is to aim at contextual representation. Thus, word2vec can be of great use, and I decided to use both the CBOW and SkipGram algorithms.

The best-performing model achieved an accuracy of 85% using the Support Vector Machine (SVM) algorithm for classification. It employed the TF-IDF (Term Frequency-Inverse Document Frequency) technique for feature extraction and underwent preprocessing using the second option for manual preprocessing and stemming. In this manual preprocessing step, we converted all text to lowercase, removed stopwords and punctuation, and performed stemming by iterating through each word in a document using a for loop, as opposed to utilizing textacy as in the first preprocessing option. However, it's worth noting that the dataset used for training was imbalanced. Another option considered was utilizing the SVM algorithm with TF-IDF on a balanced dataset, resulting in an overall accuracy of 78%. Although this option yielded a lower overall accuracy, the F1 score for each category exceeded 50% chance. Notably, the F1 score for the 'True' category in the best model was only 40%. Despite this, given our primary objective of maximizing accuracy, we opted for the model with the highest accuracy. Furthermore, the overall accuracy of the imbalanced data appears to be slightly better than that of the balanced data. Balancing doesn't seem to offer significant improvement in this case. Additionally, the second preprocessing method (manual with stemming) demonstrates superior results. Specifically, with a balanced dataset and the same TFIDF feature extractor, the overall accuracy of models employing the second preprocessing method can surpass 70%, compared to just over 50% with the first preprocessing method. Similarly, when applied to the same imbalanced dataset with the same TFIDF and SVM algorithm, the accuracy of the second preprocessing method can reach 85%, while the first preprocessing method achieves 79%. Regarding the feature extractor, TFIDF proves to be much more effective in predicting categories compared to Word2Vec (both CBOW and Skipgram). Models utilizing Word2Vec feature extraction yield insignificant results, capable of predicting only one category. Moreover, overall, the SVM algorithm outperforms Naive Bayes. With imbalanced data, the Naive Bayes algorithm produces models that are either worthless (unable to predict any category, 0%) or nearly worthless (able to predict only a small proportion, just 8% of the 'True' category). And with balanced data, the overall accuracy of SVM models are also slightly higher than that of Naive Bayes.

#CNN Model

cnnmodel = Sequential() # type of model 
cnnmodel.add(Embedding(MAX_NUM_WORDS, 128)) #input embedding layer, max words, number of nodes, 128 is a popular number
# rnnmodel.add(LSTM(128, dropout = 0.2, recurrent_dropout = 0.2)) #dropout means you forgot something
cnnmodel.add(Conv1D(128, 5, activation='relu')) #convolution one-dimensional network with 128 (number must matched), 5 answers, relu activation = rectified linear unit, tell the nodes to come off and on. This loosely inspired by the way brain works (neurons)
cnnmodel.add(MaxPooling1D(5)) #pooling: pull all info from all those points together
cnnmodel.add(Conv1D(128, 5, activation='relu'))# then another convolutional layer# where everything sort of turning off and on #these are hidden layers, so can't tell any particular node does. But mathematically tune the model
cnnmodel.add(MaxPooling1D(5))
cnnmodel.add(Conv1D(128, 5, activation='relu'))# not sure why 3 layers. but probably can start with 1 and then add more to see if it improves the model
cnnmodel.add(GlobalMaxPooling1D())#accross everything. 
cnnmodel.add(Dense(128, activation='relu')) #dense layer at the end especially for the output so it connects everything to everything else.
cnnmodel.add(Dense(y_train.shape[1], activation='softmax')) #output #dense layer notice that shape based on the amount of outcome (5 outcomes)
#but here for it to map onto whatever the code says #softmax: taking all those probabilities and picking the likely one like word2vec
#this sit he structure of the model

cnnmodel.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy', #calculate us getting it wrong, based on havng multiple answers, loss is a measure of how much the weights are changing with each round # so we want loss to level out ->get close to zero before you stop training the  model. And dont' want to continue to train after a loss essentially becomces zero bc overfitting the model
                #categoring crossentropy: popular for model with more than 2 outcomes                 
            optimizer = 'rmsprop', #a lot of optimizer to choose #ex: Adam statistic gradient descent method  #different types of math changes the output
            metrics = ['acc']) # end with how to get to the output  #metric to tune one: should choose accuracy bc we'd like to get the answers right
#can tune ont Val Acc as well

## CNN Example

#after building the model, now we fit it
cnnmodel.fit(x_train, y_train,
        batch_size = 128, #how many components it's getting at once. #48 batches within each epics, due to how many training examples i have.
        epochs = 10, # 5 not enough, neede these to knit.
        validation_data=(x_val, y_val))


#so we want accuracy to go up, loss to go down
#validation loss and vlidation accuracy very similar: good thing. Bc if acc on training and validation different, that implies model can only learn training data bc it's getting the answers and can't learn validation data

score, acc = cnnmodel.evaluate(test_data, test_labels)

print('Test accuracy with CNN:', acc)

#LDA Topic Model

# Create a dictionary representation of the documents.

# first create sentences
sentences = sent_tokenize(text)

# preprocess those sentences
processed_sentences = [preprocess(sent) for sent in sentences]

# create a list of ids to words (0 is cat, 1 is cheese)
dictionary = Dictionary(processed_sentences)

# create the term by document bag of words  (from document/sentence  (a list of words) into the bag-of-words format = list of (token_id, token_count) 2-tuples) 
corpus = [dictionary.doc2bow(sent) for sent in processed_sentences]

# Train the topic model

            id2word = dictionary,
            iterations = 400,

5.4. Discover topics with Guided LDA topic model¶

From the previous text summarization part, we understand that there are few main themes discussed in the debate include the Donald Trump's absence and legal battles, Ramaswamy's standout performance, aborption rights, Haley's discussion about Ukraine and Russia war, and candidates' view on different policy Therefore, we came up with the seed topic list as followed: At first, we prepared the list of words for each topic, and then ran through the word2id dictionary prepared to choose only words that are available in the text for each topic. (word2id includes the words (tokens) from the vocabulary, and the values are the corresponding indices that represent these words in the bag-of-words representation). This seed topic list is used in both Guided LDA and BERT Guided Topic Model.

  • Creating document-term matrix and mapping word2id

corpus=df['clean2'].to_list()

Trump_words = ['Donald',"Trump", "legal","support", "absent", "lead", "anti-Trump",'president','politician','government','court','convict','lawyer','campaign','debate','voter','criticism','republican','law','indictment','race','persecution','lead','skip']

Abortion_words = [word for word in Abortion_words if word in list(word2id.keys())]
Haley_words = [word for word in Haley_words if word in list(word2id.keys())]
policy_words = [word for word in policy_words if word in list(word2id.keys())]

model = glda.GuidedLDA(n_topics=5, n_iter=2000, random_state=7, refresh=20,alpha=0.01,eta=0.01)

seed_topics = {}
for t_id, st in enumerate(seed_topic_list):
for word in st:
    seed_topics[word2id[word]] = t_id
# seed_topics

model.fit(X, seed_topics=seed_topics, seed_confidence=0.15)

n_top_words = 20
topic_word = model.topic_word_
for i, topic_dist in enumerate(topic_word):
topic_words = np.array(vocab)[np.argsort(topic_dist)][:-(n_top_words+1):-1]
print('Topic {}\nWords: {}'.format(i, ' '.join(topic_words)))

In conclusion, I aimed to extract key themes from the transcript of the first Republican presidential debate of the 2024 election. The analysis utilized various techniques, such as text summarization, classification, and topic modeling, to gain insights into the content and sentiments expressed during the debate. The results revealed several main themes, including discussions about Donald Trump’s absence and legal battles, Vivek Ramaswamy’s standout performance, abortion rights, Nikki Haley’s comments on the Ukraine and Russia war, and candidates’ views on different policy issues. The interest in running this analysis stemmed from the desire to gain a comprehensive understanding of the debate’s content, recognize key moments, and uncover the candidates’ positions on critical issues. Overall, the LDA and LDA-TFIDF models seem to have some coherence in their topics, but they lack depth and specificity, while the guided LDA and BERT guided topic models that I used for my own analysis provide more coherent and interpretable topics, with a clearer focus on political events, figures, and issues, as they appear to capture more nuanced and meaningful topics compared to the basic LDA models. Among the two guided topic models, the BERT Guided Topic Model offered slightly more refined topics as it has advanced language understanding capabilities. I therefore consider Bert Guided Topic the best among the options I explored, and I could always refine the model further.
